<br>
Poseidon, like all his brothers and sisters, lived the first years of his life inside the dark stomach of his father Cronus up until the moment his brother Zeus, with the magical herb of Metis, managed to get them out of their peculiar imprisonment. However, there are also other myths in relation to the birth of the seagod. The ancient poets describe how Rhea also managed to fool her husband in the case of Poseidon. Instead of giving him the infant god to swallow, she gave him a newly born horse wrapped in swaddling clothes. Then, so that the frightening child eater would not hear the cries of the child, Rhea placed it among a herd of sheep, whose bleating drowned the infant's cries. She assigned his upbringing to the Nymph Arne. One day Cronus passed by there because he thought he could hear a child like cry, and asked Arne if there was a child closeby. She answered mockingly, 'how do you expect a child to exist here? Who is going to give birth to it, the goats, the sheep or me, who is an unmarried girl?'. Then an embarrassed Cronus left. <br>
<br>
However, from then on Arne was always on the alert in case the terrifying Titan suddenly returned to her area and found out about the child. If something like this occurred, then Poseidon would end up in his huge stomach, and she wouldn't be better off either. For this reason she called on the Telchines, deities who were similar to the Curetes of Crete, who protected Zeus. Every time the newly born cried, the wild Telchines would begin to dance, to cry out loudly and to bang their spears on the Earth. Among such panic and noise, Cronus could not hear a thing. Along with the Telchines, Oceanis Capheira took up the responsibility to look after the infant god after a request by her aunt Rhea. It is said that the divine demons gave Poseidon his almighty weapon, the trident. However, according to others it was given to him by the Cyclopes. What is more, when Poseidon grew up and became a man he met the sister of his companions, Halia, and fell in love with her. With her he had six sons. Depending on the version about his birth, he is either considered to be younger or older than Zeus. <br>
<br>
During the first years of his life he helped his brothers and sisters dethrone their father and the other Titans and to take authority into their own hands. After this event, the three sons of Cronus decided to divide the world up. Zeus proposed that they should separate the world into three kingdoms, the sky, the sea and the Underworld. Olympus and the Earth remained common to all so that the gods could visit them whenever they wanted to. As all three wanted the sky and none of them naturally wanted to reign for all their life in Hades, they drew lots. Zeus drew first and won the sky. Poseidon drew second and received the sea. Pluto immediately frowned, but quickly accepted his fate and withdrew to the darkness of his kingdom. Poseidon, however, couldn't easily accept Zeus's victory. He reluctantly accepted the result, but from then on he had to oppose and dispute his brother on many occasions, until he accepted his eternal supremacy and almighty power. Therefore, when Zeus ordered him to do something for him and the sea god refused to carry it out, Zeus sent Iris to his palace. Before she left he told her the following: 'Tell King Poseidon that his almighty brother orders him to come to Olympus at once, because he has to assign him a task. Otherwise, my terrifying anger will crush him'. Once he had received the message, and angry Poseidon went to Olympus and tried to convince the other gods that he was equivalent to the father of the gods and the people. 'All mighty Olympians, this situation must be cleared up once and for all. Our mother Rhea and Cronus had three sons, Zeus, Pluto and me. We divided our kingdoms and one of us received the sky, another the darkness of Hades and I received the foamy sea. Yet it is impossible for me to accept Zeus's threats and intimidatory behaviour.' However, the gods looked at each other and without saying a word to the king of the sea, they made him realise that they recognised Zeus as being superior. Then he realised that he would never have their support. <br>
<br>
In another incident he is presented as cooperating with Hera, Athena and Apollo to dethrone Zeus, trying to tie him with invisible chains to the sky. After their unsuccessful attempt, Zeus decided to punish his brother by sending him to work under the service of King Laomedon of Troy. The king assigned the god to build the walls of the city. However, when a year had gone by and Poseidon had finished his task, Laomedon refused to reward him as they had agreed. He even threatened to sell him as a slave. Once he regained his powers he gained revenge on the King and on all his nation. He sent a beast to the Trojan coast, which caused irreparable damage and tore many residents to pieces. The Trojans received a prophesy from an oracle, according to which they had to sacrifice Hesione, daughter of Laomedon, to Poseidon in order to get rid of the beast. The moment the beast was ready to tear the princess asunder, Hercules appeared and saved her. Another difference between Zeus and Poseidon was the attainment of Thetis. Both of the gods were enchanted by the Neraid's charms and wanted to make love to her. However, Mother Earth or Themis, prophesised that the son of Thetis would be much stronger than his father. Therefore, the two brothers fearing the worst, turned their attention elsewhere and decided to marry her with the mortal King of Phthia, Peleus. <br>
<br>
With the passing of time, Poseidon began to accept Zeus's superiority, to show obedience and to offer his help whenever it was needed. He stood by his side during the Battle of the Titans and the Battle of the Giants. He also helped his brother on other occasions. He calmed down the sea so that Zeus could pass with Europe after he had abducted her. He helped Leto find the island of Delos so she could give birth to his children, Apollo and Artemis. Finally, he also supported Io, another lover of Zeus, when the zealous Hera went after her. At a time when Greek cities were being founded, the gods decided that each become the protector of one or more cities. Temples would be erected there so that grandiose festivities and sacrifices could take place in honour of the gods. When a goddess was appointed as protector of a city, it was decided either by the remaining Olympians, by some less important deities or by the King and its residents. Poseidon unfortunately, would never get the city he laid claim to. His battle with Hera for the protection of Argolis is very well known. The gods assigned Inachus and the rivers Cephissus and Asterion as judges. They decided in favour of Hera. Then the ruler of the sea decided to get revenge. So he dried up all the sources of water in Argolis. According to another version he disturbed the sea with his trident, created a huge tidal wave and flooded the country. In the same way Poseidon was forced to concede Aegina to Zeus, Delphi to Apollo, Naxos to Dionysus and Athens to Athena. Furthermore, he had a dispute with Helius over the area of Corinth. Then Briareus who had been assigned as judge gave a coast of Corinth to Helius and the remaining part of the isthmus to Poseidon. Like all the other gods, Poseidon had a majestic palace on Olympus, which had been constructed by Hephaestus. This is where he stayed when he had to attend any important gathering of the gods, where they made important decisions. <br>
<br>
On other occasions he would go to celebrations that were organised on the highest mountain in Greece, either for a wedding of some immortal or for the birth of a new god, or the anniversary of some victory. However, since he was the ruler of the sea and he spent most of his time there, he had a golden palace in its vast sea bed. His beautiful underwater palace was decorated with corals and strange shells. The dark sea bed was lit up by huge glittering diamonds. Thousands of goldfish followed him everywhere and they would make sure that his azure tunic was always well groomed. Two giant sea horses continuously guarded the entrance to the palace every day and night. When the respected leader of the sea bed would leave his palace and rise to the surface of the sea, all the cetacean of the ocean would recognize their leader and move out of the way so that he could pass. The lawful wife of the sea god was Amphitrite, one of Nereus's daughters. When the god was passing through Naxos he came across the Nereids who were playing on the seashore with a colourful ball. Amphitrite stood out from her sisters because of her beauty and grace. Poseidon fell in love with her immediately, so he abducted her and took her to a cave where they got married and made love with each other. <br>
<br>
However, there is another version which describes the pairing of the gods much more eventful. Amphitrite didn't want Poseidon and resisted his advances. She managed to get away by diving into the blue waters of the sea and vanish. He searched all the coasts and caves of the sea in vain. He lifted rocks and dug up the sand of the sea without any success. One day when he was sitting on a rock sad and dejected a dolphin approached him and asked him why he was so depressed. After Poseidon explained, the sea cetacean promised his leader that it would find Amphitrite. The dolphin travelled for many days and found her near Africa in the area of Atlas. Then with coquetry it managed to entice Amphitrite and lead her to Poseidon. In order to thank his messenger, he placed his image among the stars as a constellation. The Nereid gave birth to three children from Poseidon, a son Triton, and two daughters, Rhode and Benthesicyme. <br>
<br>
The sea god had countless extra-marital affairs with goddesses, Nymphs and mortals, and was considered to be the father of some of the most well known bandits of ancient time and many frightening monsters. However, he also left descendants who were honoured heroes, ancestors of significant families and founders of cities. In relation to this he was more luckier than his brother Zeus. Amphitrite was not jealous of her husband like Hera. There is only one myth about the sea goddess gaining revenge. At one time when Poseidon fell in love with the Nymph Scylla, Amphitrite threw magical herbs into the spring in which she bathed, and changed the exquisite daughter into a disgusting monster. When Demeter was searching the world to find her daughter Persephone, that had been abducted by Pluto, Poseidon was madly in love with her. In her attempt to avoid Poseidon she transformed herself into a mare and hid among the horses of Oncus. The god was not deceived by her trickery, so he transformed into a stallion and made love to her without her knowing. An infuriated Demeter went to bathe in the waters of river Ladon in order to clean herself of this awful sin. From this strange union a daughter was born. Those who weren't familiar with Demeter's rituals, trembled to say her name. That is why they called her mistress or Despoena. However, a horse was also born, Arion. This was a marvellous animal. His exceptional speed saved Adrastus during the expedition of the Seven against Thebes. <br>
<br>
The god is also said to have had a similar amorous adventure with Medusa. She belonged to the generation of the Centaurs and was exceptionally beautiful. Once Poseidon came up to Earth and roamed the green valleys of Thessaly, and he met Medusa. As he couldn't resist his erotic desires, he transformed into a horse, because there was no other way he could make love to her. In Thessaly there was a temple of the virgin Athena. The goddess was enraged that such an unholy sin had taken place in one of her temples. However, she could not punish the culprit because was an immortal god and in fact belonged to an older generation than herself. For this reason she took it out on Medusa by changing her into a frightening monster, who instead of having hair had serpent locks. It was Perseus that later got rid of Medusa. From the affair with Poseidon, Medusa gave birth to Chryasor, father of the three-bodied giant Geryon, and the winged-horse Pegasus. <br>
<br>
However, it was impossible for the amorous god not to make love to Mother Earth, the most fertile goddess, although she was his grandmother. From their union Earth gave birth to a giant, Antaeus. It is said that he reigned over Libya. Whichever foreigner stepped on the soil of his country was doomed to die. The frightening Giant would challenge the stranger to a duel knowing that he would win. Indeed, he would dedicate the craniums of his victims to his father. Antaeus was invulnerable as long as he was touching his mother, Earth. At the time Hercules was looking for the golden apples of the Hesperides, he passed by Libya, fought with the Giant and strangled him by lifting him onto his shoulders. Poseidon was also considered to be the father of another beast, Busiris, who lived in Egypt and killed all the visitors to his country. However, in the end he met the same fate as Antaeus. He was killed by Hercules. Even Amycus was regarded as son of the sea god and the Nymph Melia. He lived in Vithynia and killed all those that travelled past. Polydeukis put an end to his injustices when he arrived there with the other Argonauts. It is even said that the handsome and brave hero did not kill the giant, but made him swear in the name of his father that he would never again kill a visitor. <br>
<br>
Most of the bandits that Theseus killed on his way from Troezen to Athens were children of Poseidon. Sciron, Sinis, Procrustes and Cercyon met a terrible death in the same way that they tortured travellers, after they had robbed them. According to a myth Poseidon made love to his grandaughter Alope, the daughter of Cercyon and with her had a son, Hippothous, who gave his name to the Hippothoudian race of Attica. The most well known giant son of the god was Cyclop Polyphemus, from his affair with the Nymph Thoosa. He was not related to the namesake sons of Earth. He represents blind and brutal power which is devoid of any sense of logic. Homer describes his sufferings from Odysseus, who fooled him by saying that he was called Kanenas(No one). For this action, Poseidon persecuted the King of Ithaca, during the ten-year journey to his homeland. Cycnus was considered to be the son of the sea god and Scamandrodice. He lost his life after a long battle with Achilles and was transformed into the bird of the same name (Swan). In addition, the Giant Orion came from the affair with Euryale, daughter of Minos. He gave his son the ability to walk on the waves of the sea. Finally, according to the myth, Aloades, Otus and Ephialtes were children of the god, from his affair with Iphimedeia. <br>
<br>
The fatherhood of many monsters and giants is attributed to Poseidon. When he wanted to get revenge on some mortal he would send various monsters to cause destruction. We have already referred to the monster he sent to Troy to gain revenge on King Laomedon. Once, the Nereids complained to their leader that Cassiopeia, Queen of Ethiopia, boasted that she was more beautiful than them. A furious god sent a monster to the coast of her country, which caused great catastrophes. A prophesy from the oracle said that the nation would be relieved of this misfortune, only if King Cepheus sacrificed his daughter Andromeda. However, at the moment the monster was ready to tear the beautiful princess to pieces, Perseus arrived with winged sandals and saved her. The god's adventures with Danaid Amymone are also very well known. After Poseidon had dried up the area of Argos to gain revenge on those who chose Hera, Amymone went looking for water in the forest. However, she was violently attacked by a certain Satyr. In order to save her, he struck Satyr with his trident and killed him. Then he struck a rock and caused the Lerna spring to flow continuously. His love affair brought him a son, Nauplius, who gave his name to the well known city in the Peloponese. In addition, one of the most significant heroes of ancient time, Theseus, was considered to be the son of Poseidon and Aethra. Poseidon had met her on the island of Thera. With Melanippe the sea god had twin sons, Boeotus and Aeolus, who later became the famous heroes of Boeotia and Aeolia respectively. <br>
<br>
His affair with Tyro is also significant. She was in love with the most beautiful river, Enipeus. She would walk along its banks all day waiting to see him. Poseidon who had fallen for the young lady transformed himself into the form of Enipeus and made love to her. They had two sons, Pelius and Neleus. Pelius reigned over Thessaly and Neleus settled down in Messenia and founded the city of Pylus. Poseidon also made love to Neleus's wife, Chloris, and gained a son called Periclymenus, and gave him the ability to transform into whatever animal he desired. From Cleite he gained Atlas, Melantho gave birth to Delphus, who gave his name to Delphi, Corcyra gave birth to Phaeax, and Rhode bore him Ialyssus, Cameirus and Lindus, who gave their names to the three most important cities of Rhodes. As the god of the sea, Poseidon was responsible for the heavy rough seas and torrential downpour that he caused with his trident, but also for the calm sea and safe voyages of sailors. For this reason the latter regarded him as their protector. Moreover, immediately after the Argonauts had successfully completed their expedition they dedicated their ship, the fast travelling Argo, to Poseidon. However, fishermen also prayed and made sacrifices to the god so that he would bring them good fish. The ancient Greeks believed that Poseidon tamed horses, and for this reason honoured him with horse races. Gifts that were usually sacrificed to him were horses and bulls. Fishermen would sacrifice fish. The sea god was worshipped all over the Greek state. Temples existed at most capes, like Sunium, Taenarus, Maleas, and elsewhere. Apart from the trident, other symbols of the god were fish, in particular tuna, the dolphin and less commonly known were the bull and horse.<br>
