Poseidon once claimed possession of Attica by striking his trident into the Acropolis at Athens, and causing sea water to gush out. Athena took possession by planting the first olive tree there. Poseidon, in a rage, challenged her to single combat, but Zeus interposed. Zeus ordered them to submit the dispute to arbitration. They appeared before a divine court, consisting of their fellow deities. After testimony was given the vote was taken: the gods voted for Poseidon (Zeus abstained), and the goddesses voted for Athena. Thus, by a majority of one, the court ruled Athena had right to the land, having given the better gift.<br>
<br>
So vexed was Poseidon that he sent huge waves against Athens. To appease Poseidon's wrath, the women of Athens were deprived of their vote.<br>
